LI. But among our chief medieinal plants is rue. tene. The cultivated kind has the wider leaves and the more bushy branches3 the wild variety is harsh in its effects and sharper in all respects. The juice is extracted by pounding with a moderate sprinkling of water, and is kept in a eopper box. An overdose of this juiee possesses poisonous qualities, especially in Macedonia near the river Aliae-mon. Strangely enough, it is neutralized by the juice of hemlock; so there are actually poisons of poisons, and hemloek juice is good for the hands and face of those who gather rue. Further, rue, especially the Gallie variety, is one of the chief ingredients of antidotes. Any sort of rue, however, is even by itself a powerful antidote, the pounded leaves being taken in wine, especially against aconite and mistletoe3 likewise, whether given in drink or in food, against poisonous fungi. In like manner it counteracts the bites of serpents, seeing that weasels, when about to fight with them, first protect themselves by eating rue. Rue is good for stings of scorpions and for those of spiders, bees, hornets and wasps, for injuries caused by cantharidesa and salamanders, and for the bites of mad dogs.
